I'm a Christian and I've never proselytized anyone (especially not rabbis!). I have people of other religions knock on the door occasionally. I may choose to listen or not, depending on my mood. But I admire their volunteer service to their church and their strong beliefs. I not sure what's to be admired about being an atheist, but you certainly don't bother me with your belief (or non-belief, as the case may be). The group of atheists posting here, though, certainly seem to have a lot of hatred for non-atheists, which is disappointing. &#10;Interestingly, one of my best friends calls herself an atheist or agnostic. However, she is one of the most spiritual people I know. I think she simply doesn't like organized religion. One of her life-long best friends was a Christian minister; she sang in a number of church choirs for many years and enjoyed the fellowship. She never had a need to put down anyone who was a &quot;believer.&quot; Nor did she try to convert anyone. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1260" language="en" documentId="1336" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="k.alan" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tempers-flare-over-prayer-in-schools-1.1104775" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1336" notes="" title="Tempers flare over prayer in schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="292"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="293" end="836"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="837" end="1260"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>